      <div class="rl-container-large">
        <div class="rl-padding-section-small">
          <div class="rl_cta8_component">
            <div class="rl_cta8_heading-wrapper">
              <h3 class="rl-heading-style-h1">Meet Jolicia.</h3>
              <div class="rl_cta8_spacing-block-1"></div>
              <p class="rl-text-style-medium">Jolicia is many things: a mother, a healthcare worker, an activist, and a voice for her community. Like you, she knows you&#x27;re many things too. Whether you&#x27;re working two jobs or the sole breadwinner, a local fixer or a rabble-rouser, unable to work or working extra as a caretaker for a loved one—we working folks are many things. You need someone to look out for you and yours and Jolicia is your woman for the job.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <header class="rl_section_header62">
    <div class="rl-padding-global">
      <div class="rl-container-large">
        <div class="rl-padding-section-medium">
          <div class="w-richtext">
            <p><strong>Jolicia Ward is an accomplished activist, advocate, former Candidate for the Virginia House of Delegates in District 99, former full-time healthcare professional for both the Department of Defense for the United States Army, and current local healthcare worker.</strong></p>
            <p>‍</p>
            <p><strong>Prior to activism and politics, Ward achieved her bachelor’s degree in mass communication from The University of Virginia, College at Wise, and her master’s degree in Entrepreneurial Management from Stratford University. Her expertise in Entrepreneurship is the reason why she has become passionate about small and local business owners and created a policy platform with multiple ways in which she will assist local entrepreneurs in her district.</strong></p>
            <p>‍</p>
            <p><strong>Ward then worked for the Department of Defense Civilian, Defense Health Agency, for The United States Army at multiple Military Treatment Facilities. Ward was honored to provide Medical Care for active-duty service members, reserves, military family members, and now all Virginians. This is why she is leading the fight for both better access to healthcare and affordable healthcare for all Virginians. She also knows that Broadband which provides access to the highest quality internet services is critical for her communities because it is needed for telehealth which requires a large amount of data transmission.</strong></p>
            <p>‍</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p><strong>Layered by activism, healthcare, education, and politics, Ward is known for her willingness to risk her own personal needs to manage the urgent needs that all people should have equal access to wealth, health, well-being, justice, privileges, and opportunity regardless of their legal, political, or economic circumstances.</strong></p>
            <p>‍</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p><strong>Ward is a proud board member of The Ralphe Bunche Art and Humanity Center, a member of the KG NAACP member, a member of the King George Democratic Committee, a Former Administrative Assistant for Rural Urban Bridge Initiative, and has worked alongside many organizations such as The African American Redress Network and Resolutions Addressing Systemic and Structural Racism. Ward has also attended several political training courses in The Commonwealth of Virginia such as Meet Our Moment, The Virginia Progressive Leadership Project, and Emerge.</strong></p>
            <p>‍</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p><strong>At this moment in time, Ward has established herself as a powerful leader and true representative of our American Democracy. She is still happiest when she is sharing her time with her two children Adrianna and Elijah and digging into the history of her counties, towns, and neighborhoods. A chief of the Upper Mattaponi Indian Tribe in King William, Virginia shared with Ward that we should always honor the past while imagining the future.</strong></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
